<p><b>Debt</b> is that which is <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/owed" class="extiw" title="wikt:owed">owed</a>; usually referencing <a href="/wiki/Assets" title="Assets" class="mw-redirect">assets</a> owed, but the term can also cover <a href="/wiki/Morality" title="Morality">moral</a> obligations and other interactions not requiring money. In the case of assets, debt is a means of using future <a href="/wiki/Purchasing_power" title="Purchasing power">purchasing power</a> in the present before a <a href="/wiki/Sum" title="Sum" class="mw-redirect">summation</a> has been earned. Some <a href="/wiki/Company" title="Company">companies</a> and <a href="/wiki/Corporation" title="Corporation">corporations</a> use debt as a part of their overall <b><a href="/wiki/Corporate_finance" title="Corporate finance">corporate finance</a></b> strategy.<sup class="noprint Template-Fact"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources&#160;since September 2008" style="white-space: nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</span></sup></p>
<p>A debt is created when a <a href="/wiki/Creditor" title="Creditor">creditor</a> agrees to <a href="/wiki/Loan" title="Loan">lend</a> a sum of assets to a <a href="/wiki/Debtor" title="Debtor">debtor</a>. In modern society, debt is usually granted with expected repayment; in many cases, plus <a href="/wiki/Interest" title="Interest">interest</a>. Historically, debt was responsible for the creation of <a href="/wiki/Indentured_servant" title="Indentured servant">indentured servants</a>.</p>
